"response_text": "The model simulates systemic dynamics in common property grazing systems, revealing complex interactions between behavioral strategies, environmental stochasticity, and adaptive capacity. Knowledge-based agents (E-RO-SL1) initially exhibit high variability in deviations (~0.3-0.7), peaking at timestep 50 before gradual stabilization (~0.2-0.4). This suggests these agents achieve equilibrium through social learning interactions within their knowledge radius (1 unit), with knowledge accumulation overcoming initial herd size imbalances. Risk-aware agents (E-LBD) maintain more stable deviations (~0.1-0.3) through individual learning cycles, demonstrating reduced susceptibility to extreme deviations compared to social learners. Traditional agents (E-RO) show patterns characteristic of anchored decision-making, with delayed convergence to stable deviations (~0.15-0.35) after initial satisficing trials dominated by herd size adjustments. The data suggests that while risk sensitivity provides short-term stability, social learning enables long-term adaptation to climate shocks (amplified by \\*\\*global-rain?\\*=True*), though at the cost of increased initial volatility. Herd size management patterns indicate that optimal equilibrium sizes vary across strategies, with knowledge-based agents achieving lower average deviations through behavioral flexibility."  
}

